data.content:
Your code **doesn't use `Thread.Abort`**, so it won't throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 8. However, the raw `Thread` pattern has no cancellation support — which is likely *why* you're auditing this.

**Key facts for your migration:**

| | .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `ThreadAbortException` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| Cancellation | Cooperative or forced | Cooperative only (`CancellationToken`) |

**Recommended modernization** — replace raw threads with `Task` + `CancellationToken`:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items, CancellationToken ct = default)
    {
        var tasks = items.Select(item => Task.Run(() => Process(item, ct), ct));
        await Task.WhenAll(tasks);
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item, CancellationToken ct)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        // simulate work
        Thread.Sleep(100); // consider Task.Delay in async contexts
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

**If you find `Thread.Abort()` elsewhere in the codebase**, replace it with:

```csharp
// Before (.NET Framework)
thread.Abort();

// After (.NET 8) — cooperative cancellation
var cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
cts.Cancel(); // signals the token; worker checks ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()
```

**Quick grep to find all `Thread.Abort` calls** in your project:

```
grep -rn "\.Abort()" --include="*.cs" .
```

The pattern is always the same: replace forced termination with cooperative `CancellationToken` checks at safe points in your work loop.
